''Dragon Quest'' was released in Japan in [[1986 in video gaming|1986]] for the Famicom, the MSX,<ref name="25thanniv">{{cite web |last=Ramos |first=Cassandra |title=''Dragon Quest Collection'' to Come With Bonus ''Dragon Quest&nbsp;X'' Video |publisher=RPGamer |date=June 30, 2011 |access-date=July 14, 2011 |url=http://www.rpgamer.com/news/Q2-2011/063011b.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704015606/http://www.rpgamer.com/news/Q2-2011/063011b.html |archive-date=July 4, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=Dragon Quest|developer=Chunsoft|publisher=Enix|date=1986|platform=MSX|scene=Title screen}}</ref> the MSX2, and the PC-9801.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Dragon Quest'' (PC98)|website=[[GameSpot]]|access-date=July 30, 2011|url=http://www.gamespot.com/pc98/rpg/dragonquest/index.html}}</ref>

''Dragon Warrior'' was released in North America by [[Nintendo of America]] under the direction of [[Satoru Iwata]] with help from Horii in August&nbsp;[[1989 in video gaming|1989]] – months before the Japanese release of ''[[Dragon Quest IV: Chapters of the Chosen|Dragon Quest&nbsp;IV]]''.<ref name=PowerUp2>{{cite book | title=Power-Up: How Japanese Video Games Gave the World an Extra Life | publisher=BradyGames |location=Indianapolis, IN |last=Kohler |first=Chris | year=2004 | pages=222–223 | isbn=978-0-7440-0424-3 | chapter=8 – Lost in Translation: This Game are Sick}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ds/interview/ydqj/vol1/index.html |title=社長が訊く『ドラゴンクエストIX 星空の守り人』 |access-date=September 28, 2011 |trans-title=The president interviews the "''Dragon Quest IX'' team" |publisher=Nintendo |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007030724/http://www.nintendo.co.jp/ds/interview/ydqj/vol1/index.html |archive-date=October 7, 2011 }}</ref> Because the game was released in North America nearly three years after the original release in Japan, the graphics were improved. Instead of lengthy [[password (video games)|password]]s with [[kana]] characters, the North American version has a battery-backed RAM savegame.<ref name=kurt /> Akira Toriyama's artwork in the instruction booklets was changed to reflect a more traditional tone of popular American based RPGs such as the [[Ultima (series)|''Ultima'' series]]. The character sprites were changed to face their direction of travel; in the Japanese versions, the sprites are smaller and face only forward, requiring players to choose a direction for actions from a menu. Spells were given self-explanatory one-word titles instead of the made-up words of the Japanese version. Locations were renamed, and dialogue was rewritten from its whimsical style comparable to ''Dragon Ball'' to a style inspired by [[Elizabethan English]],<ref name=kurt/><ref name="Roleplayer's Realm"/> with sentences such as "Thy hit points have decreased by 1."<ref name=PowerUp2/> Nintendo also removed salacious humor and religious connotations from the English-language version.<ref name=PowerUp2/> For example, in the Japanese version, in the town where the hero first buys keys, a woman offers to sell [[Puff-puff (Dragon Quest)|puff-puff]]{{mdash}}a Japanese [[onomatopoeia]] for a girl rubbing her breasts in someone's face, or juggling her own breasts. In the North American version, the same woman sells tomatoes.<ref name="np238_84"/> The term has been included in the game's sequels as well as in Toriyama's ''Dragon Ball'' series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kauz |first=Andrew |title=The rubbing of breasts on faces in ''Dragon Quest&nbsp;IX'' |website=[[Destructoid]] |date=August 21, 2010 |access-date=July 14, 2011 |url=http://www.destructoid.com/the-rubbing-of-breasts-on-faces-in-dragon-quest-ix-181483.phtml |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110925153518/http://www.destructoid.com/the-rubbing-of-breasts-on-faces-in-dragon-quest-ix-181483.phtml |archive-date=September 25, 2011 }}</ref>

[[Katsuya Terada]] created some of the artwork for the early ''Dragon Warrior'' articles in ''Nintendo Power''. Neither Terada nor those editing the artwork for the instruction booklet followed Toriyama's work; they instead used the settings and character poses to create alternate artwork in an American style.<ref name=Art>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.gamepro.com/article/features/219639/the-art-of-dragon-quest/ |title=The Art of Dragon Quest |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111202212151/http://www.gamepro.com/article/features/219639/the-art-of-dragon-quest/ |archive-date=2011-12-02 |magazine=[[GamePro]] |date=2011-05-25 |access-date=2011-08-03 |author=Oxford, Nadia |url-status=dead}}</ref> The Japanese hero has a [[Chibi (style)|chibi]] manga style, and the English version's appearance is based on "the West's template of a medieval hero".<ref name=Art/>

In June 1989, ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]''{{'}}s "Quartermann" speculated that ''Dragon Warrior'' would be Nintendo's "big release" in North America that Christmas based on the immense popularity of the series in Japan, especially ''[[Dragon Quest&nbsp;III]]''.<ref name="EGM 1989">{{cite magazine |author=Quartermann |title=Gaming Gossip |magazine=Electronic Gaming Monthly |issue=2 |date=June 1989 |page=26 |publisher=Sendai Publications |location=Lombard, IL |issn=1058-918X |oclc=23857173}}</ref> ''Nintendo Power'' provided three feature articles on ''Dragon Warrior'' for issues between May and October&nbsp;1989<ref name="NP8" /><ref name="np6_52"/><ref name=np7_40/> and the November–December&nbsp;1989 issue includes a [[strategy guide]].<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=Table of Contents|magazine=Nintendo Power|date=November–December 1989|issue=9|publisher=Tokuma Shoten |location=Redmond, WA |issn=1041-9551 |oclc=18893582|page=5}}</ref> The March–April&nbsp;1990 issue of ''Nintendo Power'' has a map of the game world, with a poster of ''[[Super Contra]]'' on the other side, and a ''Dragon Warrior'' text adventure.<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=''Dragon Warrior'' Text Adventure|magazine=Nintendo Power|date=March–April 1990|issue=11|publisher=Tokuma Shoten |location=Redmond, WA |issn=1041-9551 |oclc=18893582|pages=51–54}}</ref>

In late 1990, Nintendo reportedly strategized the unloading of unsold game units<ref name="1UP-flops">{{cite web |last=Mackey |first=Bob |title=Smart Bombs: Celebrating Gaming's Most Beloved Flops |website=1UP.com |date=February 5, 2007 |access-date=July 11, 2011 |url=http://www.1up.com/features/smart-bombs |page=2 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151127003318/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=1&cId=3165915 |archive-date=November 27, 2015 }}</ref> by sending free copies of ''Dragon Warrior'' to ''Nintendo Power'' subscribers,<ref name="1UP.com" /> including a 64-page ''Explorer's Handbook'' with a full walkthrough of the game and additional backstory.<ref>{{cite book |title=''Dragon Warrior'' Explorer's Handbook |publisher=Nintendo of America |location=Redmond, WA |year=1989 |id=NES-DQA-USA}}</ref> At the time, the game cost approximately {{USD|50|1989|about=yes}} at retail and the magazine's subscription fee was only {{USD|20|long=no}}.<ref name=PowerUp2/> The giveaway attracted nearly 500,000 new magazine subscribers, and many more renewed subscriptions just to get the game.<ref name=PowerUp2/><ref name="1UP-flops" /><ref>{{cite magazine|title=50 Issues of ''Nintendo Power'': A View from Inside Out |magazine=Nintendo Power |publisher=Tokuma Shoten |issue=50 |date=July 1993 |location=Redmond, WA |issn=1041-9551 |oclc=18893582 |page=39}}</ref> This ultimately led to the success of the series in the Western market.<ref name="1UP-flops" />

===Re-releases and remakes===
[[File:Dragon Quest 1 Remake screenshot.png|thumb|right|''Dragon Quest'' was updated for the Super Famicom. Tantegel Castle (center) is the hero's starting location, and the Dragonlord's Charlock Castle is the goal (bottom-right).|alt=A two-dimensional video game screenshot that shows the protagonist in front of a castle. The graphics are more detailed than those in the previous game images.]]
Enix [[Video game remake|remade]] ''Dragon Quest'' and ''[[Dragon Quest&nbsp;II]]'' for the single-cartridge compilation ''Dragon Quest I & II'' for the Super Famicom on December&nbsp;18, 1993. More than 1.2&nbsp;million copies were sold in Japan.<ref name="Hitmitsu">{{cite web|last=Hitmitsu |first=Suppai |title=''Dragon Quest&nbsp;V'' Breaks Record |website=IGN |date=April 8, 2004 |access-date=July 24, 2011 |url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/505/505072p1.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050212232209/http://ps2.ign.com/articles/505/505072p1.html |archive-date=February 12, 2005 }}</ref> In 1998, Enix released ''BS Dragon Quest'' for the Super Famicom via the [[Satellaview]] peripheral exclusively in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|title=''BS Dragon Quest'' |website=GameSpot |access-date=July 24, 2011 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/snes/rpg/bsdragonquest/index.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904025152/http://www.gamespot.com/snes/rpg/bsdragonquest/index.html |archive-date=September 4, 2009 }}</ref> The latter consists of four one-hour scenarios downloaded on a weekly schedule. The player is tasked with leveling the character, collecting medals, and completing scenario-specific conditions with special [[real-time game|real-time]] events.<ref name=Microgroup>{{cite web | url=http://www.microgroup.co.jp/gamesoft/128004.php | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060827215928/http://www.microgroup.co.jp/gamesoft/128004.php |archive-date=August 27, 2006 |url-status=dead | script-title=ja:ＢＳドラゴンクエスト リアルタイムを考慮した巧みな演出を | publisher=Micro Group | access-date=October 25, 2011 | author=Hayashi Mura Wataru |trans-title=BS Dragon Quest: Evaluating the Skillful Real-time Event Production  | language=ja}}</ref>

The compilation was re-released for the GBC, developed by [[Tose (company)|Tose]] and released by Enix on September 23, 1999, in Japan and September 27, 2000, in North America.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=International Outlook |magazine=Electronic Gaming Monthly |publisher=Sendai Publications |location=Lombard, IL |issn=1058-918X |oclc=23857173 |issue=149 |date=December 2001 |page=51}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Provo |first=Frank |title=''Dragon Warrior&nbsp;I&nbsp;&&nbsp;II'' Review |website=GameSpot |date=September 29, 2000 |access-date=August 13, 2011 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/gbc/rpg/dragonwarrior1_2/review.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070109235234/http://www.gamespot.com/gbc/rpg/dragonwarrior1_2/review.html |archive-date=2007-01-09 |url-status=dead}}</ref> It uses an entirely new translation, discards the pseudo-Elizabethan English style and uses names closer to those in the Japanese version.<ref name=":IGN DW1&2"/><ref name="np238_84"/> In this remake, "Dragonlord" is changed to "DracoLord", and "Erdrick" is changed to "Loto". Several additional features were added such as where the player can [[quicksave]] the game anytime outside a battle.<ref name=Johnson/><ref name="DW1&2GBC"/> Players can store some gold.<ref name=":IGN DW1&2"/> The menu was streamlined and monsters yield more experience and gold, saving time.<ref name="DW1&2GBC"/>

In 2004, ''Dragon Quest'' and its sequel were remade for mobile phones in Japan. These are graphically based on the Super Famicom remake of ''[[Dragon Quest III]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://woodus.com/den/games/dq1mob/screenshots.php |title=Dragon's Den > Dragon Quest 1 Mobile > Screenshots |access-date=November 21, 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121200723/http://woodus.com/den/games/dq1mob/screenshots.php |archive-date=November 21, 2015 }}</ref> and ''[[Dragon Quest VI: Realms of Revelation|Dragon Quest VI]]''.<ref>{{cite web|year=2004 |title=''Dragon Quest'' for Mobile Phones |website=GameSpot |url=http://www.gamespot.com/mobile/rpg/dragonquest/index.html |access-date=October 14, 2007 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007073751/http://www.gamespot.com/mobile/rpg/dragonquest/index.html |archive-date=October 7, 2007 }}</ref>

On September 15, 2011, the ''Dragon Quest 25th Anniversary Collection'' compilation for the [[Wii]] was released in Japan, containing the Famicom version, Super Famicom version, ''Dragon Quest II'', and ''Dragon Quest III''. It includes original copies of the games' strategy guides, original artwork, and development material.<ref name="25thanniv" /> In October 2013, Square Enix announced the re-release of ''Dragon Quest I–VIII'' for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Seppala |first=Timothy J. |title=''Dragon Quest'' Series Coming to Android and iOS this Winter |publisher=[[Engadget]] |date=October 9, 2013 |access-date=October 18, 2013 |url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/10/09/square-enix-dragon-quest-android-ios/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019133412/http://www.engadget.com/2013/10/09/square-enix-dragon-quest-android-ios/ |archive-date=October 19, 2013 }}</ref> In November 2013, the game was released for iOS and Android in Japan, based on the 2004 mobile remake. The United States and Europe mobile versions were released on September 11, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-09-11-the-first-dragon-quest-launches-on-ios-and-android |title=The first Dragon Quest launches on iOS and Android |last1=Yin-Poole |first1=Wesley |date=September 11, 2014 |website=[[Eurogamer]] |access-date=2014-09-11 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912021812/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-09-11-the-first-dragon-quest-launches-on-ios-and-android |archive-date=September 12, 2014 }}</ref>

In the [[Nintendo Direct]] in September 2019, Nintendo confirmed that ''Dragon Quest'', ''II'' and ''III'', would be released on the Nintendo Switch on September 27, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gematsu.com/2019/09/dragon-quest-i-ii-and-iii-coming-to-switch-on-september-27-in-japan|title=Dragon Quest I, II, and III coming to Switch on September 27 in Japan|website=Gematsu|date=4 September 2019|access-date=September 10, 2019}}</ref>

In the Nintendo Direct in June 2024, a HD-2D remake of ''Dragon Quest'' and ''II'' was announced to be released in 2025 for [[Microsoft Windows]], Nintendo Switch, [[PlayStation 5]] and [[Xbox Series X/S]].<ref name="dqi-&-II-HD-2D-RE"/>

==Related media==
''Dragon Warrior'' has inspired related media in the form of a manga series, which has been adapted to anime, and a [[symphony|symphonic]] [[video game soundtrack]].

===Anime and manga===
The manga series, {{nihongo3|''Dragon Quest Saga: Emblem of Roto''|ドラゴンクエスト列伝 ロトの紋章|''Dragon Quest Retsuden: Roto no Monshō''}}, was written by [[Chiaki Kawamata]] and Junji Koyanagi, with artwork by [[Kamui Fujiwara]], and was published between 1991 and 1997 by ''[[Monthly Shōnen Gangan]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.square-enix.co.jp/magazine/yg/roto/ |script-title=ja:ドラゴンクエスト列伝 ロトの紋章 完全版 |trans-title=Full version of ''Dragon Quest Saga: Emblem of Roto'' |publisher=Square Enix |access-date=November 9, 2009 |language=ja |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091019235047/http://www.square-enix.co.jp/magazine/yg/roto/ |archive-date=October 19, 2009 }}</ref> Enix compiled the series into 21&nbsp;volumes,<ref>{{Cite book|script-title=ja:ロトの紋章―ドラゴンクエスト列伝 (21) (ガンガンコミックス) (コミック)|trans-title=''Dragon Quest Saga: Roto's Emblem'' (21) (Young Gangan) (Comic)|publisher=Amazon|language=ja|id= {{ASIN|4870252058|country=jp}}}}</ref> which were later released on compact disc in 1994. It was released on December&nbsp;11, 2009 for the [[PlayStation Store]] as part of the initial launch of Sony's digital comic distribution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-09-24/japan-sony-psp-manga-distribution-service-detailed |title=Japan's Sony PSP Manga Distribution Service Detailed |publisher=Anime News Network |work=News |date=September 24, 2009 |access-date=November 9, 2009 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091124081540/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-09-24/japan-sony-psp-manga-distribution-service-detailed |archive-date=November 24, 2009 }}</ref> In 1996, an anime movie based on the manga was released on videocassette.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B00005G2N6|title=ドラゴンクエスト列伝・ロトの紋章 [VHS]|date=20 December 1996 |trans-title=''Dragon Quest Saga: Emblem of Roto'' [VHS]|publisher=Amazon|access-date=November 9, 2009|language=ja}}</ref> Square Enix started publishing a sequel series, {{nihongo3|''Dragon Quest Retsuden: Emblem of Roto – To the Children Who Inherit the Emblem''|ドラゴンクエスト列伝 ロトの紋章 ～紋章を継ぐ者達へ～|''Dragon Quest Retsuden: Roto no Monshō ~Monshō o Tsugumono-tachi e~''}}, in 2005.<ref name=Roto9>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-11-04/japanese-comic-ranking-october-26-november-1 |title=Japanese Comic Ranking, October 26 – November 1 |publisher=Anime News Network |work=News |date=November 4, 2009 |access-date=November 9, 2009 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091107074456/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-11-04/japanese-comic-ranking-october-26-november-1 |archive-date=November 7, 2009 }}</ref>  {{Interlanguage link multi|Jun Eishima|ja|3=永嶋恵美}} wrote the first four volumes, and Takashi Umemura wrote the last five; Yuji Horii supervised the manga, and Kamui Fujiwara contributed the artwork.<ref name="manga sequel">{{cite web|url=http://www.square-enix.co.jp/magazine/yg/introduction/rotomon/ |script-title=ja:ドラゴンクエスト列伝 ロトの紋章 ～紋章を継ぐ者達へ～ |trans-title=Dragon Quest Retsuden: Roto no Monshō – To the Children Who Inherit the Emblem |publisher=Square Enix |access-date=November 9, 2009 |language=ja |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105214052/http://www.square-enix.co.jp/magazine/yg/introduction/rotomon/ |archive-date=November 5, 2012 }}</ref>

''Dragon Quest Saga: Emblem of Roto'' takes place between ''Dragon Warrior&nbsp;III'' and ''Dragon Warrior''. After monsters possessed Carmen's king for seven years, the kingdom fell to the hordes of evil. The only survivors were Prince Arus and an army General's daughter, Lunafrea. Meanwhile, in the Kingdom of Loran, a child is born and is named Jagan in accordance with the demon lord Imagine's orders. Arus and Lunafrea set out to defeat the monsters and restore peace to the world.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dqshrine.com/ma/eor/ | title=Emblem of Roto | access-date=April 10, 2011 | publisher=The Dragon Quest Dragon Warrior Shrine |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061028153843/http://www.dqshrine.com/ma/eor/ |archive-date=2006-10-28 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The sequel, ''To the Children Who Inherit the Emblem'', takes place five years after the events in ''Dragon Quest Saga: Emblem of Roto''. The world is again in chaos and a young boy, {{nihongo|Arosu|アロス}}, sets out to gather companions to help him save the world from evil.<ref name="manga sequel"/>

===Soundtrack===
[[Koichi Sugiyama]] composed and directed the music for ''Dragon Warrior''.<ref name="EGM"/> The soundtrack included eight tracks, which ''RPGFan'' said was "the foundation for Sugiyama's career".<ref name="SymSuiteDQ">{{cite web|url=http://rpgfan.com/soundtracks/dq1/index.html |title=''Symphonic Suite Dragon Quest&nbsp;I'' |last=Gann |first=Patrick |date=May 15, 2008 |publisher=RPGFan |access-date=December 1, 2009 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091230083138/http://rpgfan.com/soundtracks/dq1/index.html |archive-date=December 30, 2009 }}</ref> The pieces were arranged and incorporated into later ''Dragon Warrior'' games' soundtracks.<ref name="SymSuiteDQ"/> The music has been released in a variety of formats. The first is as a [[Radio drama in Japan|Drama&nbsp;CD]], released by Enix on July&nbsp;19, 1991, which incorporated a narrated story.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rpgfan.com/soundtracks/dq1-drama/index.html |title=CD Theater ''Dragon Quest&nbsp;I'' |last=Gann |first=Patrick |date=September 13, 2001 |publisher=RPGFan |access-date=December 1, 2009 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091230123339/http://rpgfan.com/soundtracks/dq1-drama/index.html |archive-date=December 30, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.squareenixmusic.com/albums/d/dq1theater.shtml |title=''Dragon Quest&nbsp;I'' CD Theater |access-date=April 10, 2011 |publisher=Square Enix Music Online |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106034104/http://www.squareenixmusic.com/albums/d/dqpiano1.shtml |archive-date=January 6, 2009 }}</ref> ''Super Famicom Edition Symphonic Suite Dragon Quest&nbsp;I'', published by [[Sony Records]] on January&nbsp;12, 1994, followed; the soundtrack featured orchestral versions of the tracks played by the [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]] and the original versions of the tunes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rpgfan.com/soundtracks/dq1-sfc/index.html |title=Super Famicom Edition ''Symphonic Suite Dragon Quest&nbsp;I'' |last=Gann |first=Patrick |date=November 18, 2008 |publisher=RPGFan |access-date=December 1, 2009 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091230054136/http://rpgfan.com/soundtracks/dq1-sfc/index.html |archive-date=December 30, 2009 }}</ref> The game's classical score was considered revolutionary for console game music.<ref name="1up_dw">{{cite web|last=Gifford|first=Kevin|title=The Essential 50 Part 20 - Dragon Warrior|url=http://www.1up.com/features/essential-50-dragon-warrior|website=[[1UP.com]]|access-date=May 15, 2011|archive-date=January 2, 2013|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130102043453/http://www.1up.com/features/essential-50-dragon-warrior|url-status=dead}}</ref> The soundtrack's "eight melodies" approach set the template for most RPG soundtracks released since then, hundreds of which have been organized in a similar manner.<ref>{{cite web|title=The "Eight Melodies" Template: How Sugiyama Shaped RPG Soundtracks |url=http://www.rpgfan.com/editorials/2008/11-29.html |publisher=RPGFan |access-date=September 4, 2011 |last=Gann |first=Patrick |date=29 November 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111016020559/http://rpgfan.com/editorials/2008/11-29.html |archive-date=October 16, 2011 }}</ref>

The orchestral albums for ''Dragon Warrior&nbsp;I''&nbsp;and&nbsp;''II'' were combined in ''Symphonic Suite Dragon Quest&nbsp;I•II'', released by [[SME&nbsp;Visual Works]] on August&nbsp;23, 2000, [[King Records (Japan)|King Records]] reprinted it on October&nbsp;7, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rpgfan.com/soundtracks/dq1&2/index.html |title=Super Famicom Edition ''Symphonic Suite Dragon Quest&nbsp;I'' |last=Prievert |first=Alexander |date=February 7, 2006 |publisher=RPGFan |access-date=December 1, 2009 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091230061335/http://rpgfan.com/soundtracks/dq1%262/index.html |archive-date=December 30, 2009 }}</ref> The orchestral tracks were again released in the ''Symphonic Suite Dragon Quest&nbsp;I'' album, including orchestral versions of the game's sound effects.<ref name="SymSuiteDQ"/>  Numerous live concerts have featured performances of the game's music; many performances were later released as albums such as ''Dragon Quest in Concert'' and ''Suite Dragon Quest&nbsp;I•II''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Patrick Gann |year=2007 |title=''Dragon Quest'' in Concert |publisher=RPGfan |url=http://www.rpgfan.com/soundtracks/dq-ic/index.html |access-date=August 31, 2007 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821134300/http://www.rpgfan.com/soundtracks/dq-ic/index.html |archive-date=August 21, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rpgfan.com/soundtracks/dq1&2-suite/index.html |title=''Suite Dragon Quest I•II'' |last=Gann |first=Patrick |date=October 27, 2009 |publisher=RPGFan |access-date=December 1, 2009 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091230082644/http://rpgfan.com/soundtracks/dq1%262-suite/index.html |archive-date=December 30, 2009 }}</ref>

