===NES version===
Initial sales of the game were so low that Enix was going to lose money, but several ''[[Weekly Shōnen Jump|Shonen Jump]]'' articles by Horii helped increase its sales substantially. People liked Toriyama's artwork and Sugiyama's music, which the book ''Power-Up: How Japanese Video Games Gave the World an Extra Life'' said "was richer and more exciting than any game music had ever sounded".<ref name=PowerUp/> In Japan, 1.5 million copies of the original version were sold.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/71808/full/ | title=ドラクエ9、シリーズ最高415万本出荷 | language=Japanese | work=Oricon News | date=December 21, 2009 | access-date=March 21, 2021}}</ref> More than {{nowrap|1 million}} of those copies were sold within the first six months.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Iwamoto |first1=Yoshiyuki |title=Japan on the Upswing: Why the Bubble Burst and Japan's Economic Renewal |date=2006 |publisher=Algora Publishing |isbn=978-0-87586-463-1 |page=201 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sUUehPO7CdwC&pg=PA201}}</ref> It was very successful there and launched a popular series with several spin-off series and stand-alone games.

In the first [[Famitsu Awards|''Famitsu'' Best Hit Game Awards]] (published February 1987, for [[1986 in video games|1986 releases]]), ''Dragon Quest'' won the awards for [[List of Game of the Year awards|Game of the Year]], Best Scenario/Story, Best Character Design, Best Programmer (for [[Koichi Nakamura]]), and Best RPG.<ref name="Famitsu">{{cite magazine |title=1986 ベストヒットゲーム大賞 |trans-title=1986 Best Hit Game Awards |magazine=[[Famicom Tsūshin]] |date=6 February 1987 |volume=1987 |issue=3 |pages=[https://cdn-ak.f.st-hatena.com/images/fotolife/M/MULTi88/20190410/20190410193233.jpg 4] to [https://cdn-ak.f.st-hatena.com/images/fotolife/M/MULTi88/20190410/20190410193255.jpg 7] |lang=ja}}</ref> The 1989 "All Soft Catalog" issue of ''[[Famicom Tsūshin]]'' (''Famitsu'') includes ''Dragon Quest'' in its list of the [[List of video games considered the best|best games of all time]], receiving the Best RPG and Best Character Design [[List of Game of the Year awards|awards]], but losing to ''[[Dragon Quest III]]'' for the overall Grand Prize for best game of all time.<ref name=Famitsu1989>{{citation|magazine=[[Famitsu|Famicom Tsūshin]]| title=Famitsu | issue=All Soft Catalog '89|year=1989}}</ref>

Several years after the Japanese release, the first English version of ''Dragon Warrior'' was initially seen as a commercial failure,<ref name="1UP-flops" /> but the ''Nintendo Power'' subscription giveaway was eventually a success and allowed Enix to bring the next three games to North America. According to Chris Kohler, Nintendo profited immensely from the giveaway because "''Nintendo Power'' was essentially a hundred-page monthly ad for Nintendo products", and it was now in thousands of households.<ref name=PowerUp2/> The game sold about 500,000 copies in the United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-new-dark-age-of-dragon-quest|title=The New Dark Age of Dragon Quest|website=[[USgamer]]|date=August 21, 2013|access-date=March 13, 2021|last=Parish|first=Jeremy|archive-date=December 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191228165200/https://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-new-dark-age-of-dragon-quest|url-status=dead}}</ref> making it the third best-selling [[1989 in video games|1989 game release]] in North America, below [[List of Tetris variants|Nintendo's ''Tetris'']] and ''[[Super Mario Land]]''.<ref name="Famitsu83">{{cite magazine |title=Count Down Hot 100: USA Hot 10! |magazine=[[Famicom Tsūshin]] |date=16 April 1993 |issue=226 |page=83 |lang=ja |url=https://archive.org/details/famitsu-issue-226-apr-1993/page/83}}</ref> In total, ''Dragon Quest'' sold more than 2&nbsp;million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kohler |first1=Chris |title=Power-Up: How Japanese Video Games Gave the World an Extra Life |date=21 October 2016 |publisher=[[Courier Dover Publications]] |isbn=978-0-486-80149-0 |page=80 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lD4fDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA80}}</ref><ref name=PowerUp/>

In North America, the English version garnered average reviews overall. ''Nintendo Power'' rated it about three out of five.<ref name="np6_52"/> It debuted at No.&nbsp;7 on the magazine's bimonthly "Top&nbsp;30" top NES games list in November&nbsp;1989.<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=Top 30|magazine=Nintendo Power|date=November–December 1989|issue=9|publisher=Tokuma Shoten |location=Redmond, WA |issn=1041-9551 |oclc=18893582|page=81}}</ref> It climbed to No.&nbsp;5 in January&nbsp;1990 and remained there for 4 months;<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=Top 30|magazine=Nintendo Power|date=January–February 1990|issue=10|publisher=Tokuma Shoten |location=Redmond, WA |issn=1041-9551 |oclc=18893582|page=49}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|title=Top 30|magazine=Nintendo Power|date=March–April 1990|issue=11|publisher=Tokuma Shoten |location=Redmond, WA |issn=1041-9551 |oclc=18893582|page=41}}</ref> it then dropped to No.&nbsp;11 in May,<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=Top 30|magazine=Nintendo Power|date=May–June 1990|issue=12|publisher=Tokuma Shoten |location=Redmond, WA |issn=1041-9551 |oclc=18893582|page=43}}</ref> No.&nbsp;14 in July,<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=Top 30|magazine=Nintendo Power|date=July–August 1990|issue=14|publisher=Tokuma Shoten |location=Redmond, WA |issn=1041-9551 |oclc=18893582|page=67}}</ref> and No.&nbsp;16 in September&nbsp;1990, then leaving the list.<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=Top 30|magazine=Nintendo Power|date=September–October 1990|issue=16|publisher=Tokuma Shoten |location=Redmond, WA |issn=1041-9551 |oclc=18893582|page=23}}</ref> In the "''Nintendo Power'' Awards&nbsp;1989", the game was nominated for "Best Theme, Fun" and "Best Overall";<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=''Nintendo Power'' Awards&nbsp;'89|magazine=Nintendo Power|date=March–April 1990|issue=11|publisher=Tokuma Shoten |location=Redmond, WA |issn=1041-9551 |oclc=18893582|pages=98–99}}</ref> but did not win in either category.<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=''Nintendo Power'' Awards&nbsp;'89|magazine=Nintendo Power|date=May–June 1990|issue=12|publisher=Tokuma Shoten |location=Redmond, WA |issn=1041-9551 |oclc=18893582|pages=26–29}}</ref> In response to Japanese youths' arrests while waiting for ''Dragon Quest&nbsp;III''{{'}}s release, ''Electronic Gaming Monthly''{{'}}s Quartermann said that the game was not "that special at all", compared it to the NES version of ''[[Ultima&nbsp;III: Exodus]]'' and recommended that others play that game instead.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=Quartermann |title=Gaming Gossip |magazine=Electronic Gaming Monthly |issue=3 |date=September 1989 |page=28 |publisher=Sendai Publications |location=Lombard, IL |issn=1058-918X |oclc=23857173}}</ref>

The game's release has been regarded as important in the history of the console RPG genre.<ref name=Essential50/><ref name="spy"/> Kohler noted that Toriyama's and Sugiyama's contributions to the game "made ''Dragon Quest'' as visually and aurally exciting as the game play was unique and sophisticated".<ref name=PowerUp/> [[GameSpot]] named it as one of the fifteen most influential video games in history.<ref name="Gamespot top15">{{cite web | year=2005 | title=15 Most Influential Games|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090610012514/http://gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/15influential/p11_01.html|archive-date=June 10, 2009|url=http://www.gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/15influential/p11_01.html|website=GameSpot|access-date=September 1, 2009}}</ref> [[IGN]] listed it as the eighth best all-time NES game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/top-100-nes-games/8.html|title=Top 100 NES Games of all Time|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028131723/http://www.ign.com/top-100-nes-games/index.html|archive-date=October 28, 2009|first=Colin|last=Moriarty|website=IGN|access-date=October 16, 2009}}</ref> In 2005, it listed it as the 92nd-best all-time video game,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://top100.ign.com/2005/091-100.html |title=Top 100 Games of all Time: 091-100 |website=IGN |date=July 29, 2005 |access-date=October 27, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619235710/http://top100.ign.com/2005/091-100.html |archive-date=June 19, 2010 }}</ref> and in 2007 it listed the game as the 29th best.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://top100.ign.com/2007/ign_top_game_29.html |title=Top 100 Games of all Time: ''Dragon Warrior'' |website=IGN |date=December 3, 2007 |access-date=October 27, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100315083900/http://top100.ign.com/2007/ign_top_game_29.html |archive-date=March 15, 2010 }}</ref> ''Nintendo Power'' rated ''Dragon Warrior'' as the 140th-best game made for the Nintendo System in its Top&nbsp;200 Games list in 2006.<ref name="NP Top 200">{{Cite magazine|title=''Nintendo Power''{{'}}s Top 200 All-Time Games|magazine=Nintendo Power| date=February 2006 |issue=200|publisher=Tokuma Shoten |location=Redmond, WA |issn=1041-9551 |oclc=18893582|pages=58–66}}</ref> RPGamer's Bill Johnson gave it a 4 out of 5 overall score.<ref name=Johnson/><ref name=Roku>{{cite web|url=http://www.rpgamer.com/games/dq/dq1/reviews/dq1strev2.html |title=Here's a Stick, Go Save the World |publisher=RPGamer |access-date=April 14, 2011 |author=Calvin, Derek "Roku" |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006164837/http://www.rpgamer.com/games/dq/dq1/reviews/dq1strev2.html |archive-date=October 6, 2012 }}</ref> The NES version received considerable praise for adding extra characters and depth to the story.<ref name=kurt/><ref name=Johnson/> The removal of the stylized dialogue in the GBC remake has similarly been lamented.<ref name=":IGN DW1&2"/> [[AllGame]] declared that "despite its enormous influence [...] ''Dragon Warrior'' is a flawed game. It has some decent design ideas, but it's just not terribly enjoyable", noting simplistic graphics, slow pace, and poor sound.<ref name="ag-rev" />

Seemingly primitive by modern standards, ''Dragon Warrior'' features one-on-one combat, a limited item and equipment array, ten spells, five towns, and five dungeons.<ref name=kurt/><ref name=Johnson/><ref name="Guide 6/105"/><ref name=np7_40/> While noting its importance to the development of the RPG genre, ''[[Allgame]]'' reviewer Kyle Knight stated that "taken on its own merits, it's just not an enjoyable game to play."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=2730&tab=review |title=Dragon Warrior |publisher=[[allgame]] |access-date=2011-12-04 |author=Knight, Kyle |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100216010011/http://allgame.com/game.php?id=2730&tab=review |archive-date=2010-02-16 }}</ref> ''1UP.com'' explained that the series was not immensely popular at first in North America because American console gamers were not used to the idea of RPGs, and that it would take a decade for the genre to be "flashy enough to distract from all of those words they made you read".<ref name="1UP-flops" /> Chi Kong Lui wrote for ''GameCritics'' that the game added realism to video games, which allows players to identify with the main character on a much larger scale, saying "If a player perished in ''Dragon Warrior'', he or she had to suffer the dire consequences of losing progress and precious gold. That element of death evoked a sense of instinctive fear and tension for survival."<ref name=Gamecritics>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecritics.com/review/dragonwarr12/main.php |title=''Dragon Warrior&nbsp;I&nbsp;&&nbsp;II'' |author=Chi Kong Lui |publisher=GameCritics |date=March 2, 2001 |access-date=October 6, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060101044011/http://www.gamecritics.com/review/dragonwarr12/main.php |archive-date=2006-01-01 |url-status=dead}}</ref> ''IGN '' writer Mark Nix compared the game's seemingly archaic plot to more modern RPGs, saying, "Noble blood means nothing when the society is capitalist, aristocratic, or militaristic. Damsels don't need rescuing{{mdash}}they need a battle axe and some magic tutoring in the field."<ref name=":IGN DW1&2"/> Reviewing ''[[Dragon Quest VIII: Journey of the Cursed King]]'', ''[[GameSpy]]'' staff wrote that ''Dragon Warrior'' is many gamers' first exposure to the console RPG. Recalling their past, a staff member commented: {{blockquote|It opened my eyes to a fun new type of gameplay. Suddenly strategy (or at least pressing the "A" button) was more important than reflex, and the story was slightly (slightly!) more complex than the 'rescue the princess' stuff I'd seen up 'till then. After all, ''Dragon Warrior'' was only half-over when you rescued its princess.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespy.com/articles/618/618469p8.html | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050531011342/http://www.gamespy.com/articles/618/618469p8.html | archive-date=May 31, 2005 |title= The Annual E3 Awards 2005|work=GameSpy | publisher=IGN | access-date=November 29, 2015}}</ref>}}

Bill Johnson compared ''Dragon Warrior'' to modern RPGs and noted the game's lack of replay value, which is due to the game's requirement of total completion and to its overall difficulty. He noted the game's historical importance, saying, "[Playing ''Dragon Warrior'' is] a tough road to walk, but reaching its end will instill a new appreciation of what today's RPGs are all about."<ref name=Johnson/> The 2009 book ''Vintage Games'' contrasted ''Dragon Warrior'' to the 1986 NES game ''[[The Legend of Zelda (1986 video game)|The Legend of Zelda]]'', saying that though both games share common RPG elements, ''Zelda'' features a fantasy setting and magic but no level or turn-based combat system, and ''Dragon Warrior'' features both.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Loguidice |first1=Bill |last2=Barton |first2=Matt |title=Vintage Games |url=https://archive.org/details/vintagegamesinsi00logu_076 |url-access=limited |publisher=[[Focal Press]] |location=[[Burlington, MA]] |isbn=978-0-240-81146-8 |year=2009 |page=[https://archive.org/details/vintagegamesinsi00logu_076/page/n317 305] |chapter=21 – ''The Legend of Zelda'' (1986)}}</ref> ''Nintendo Power'' said the game's historical significance is its greatest aspect, and noted that "playing ''Dragon Warrior'' these days can be a bit of a chore".<ref name="np238_84"/> ''[[GamePro]]'' wrote that their favorite aspect of the game was the Elizabethan-English dialogue, and that they were disappointed by its removal in the GBC remake.<ref name="Roleplayer's Realm">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.gamepro.com/article/news/219727/roleplayers-realm-dragon-quest-25th-anniversary-edition/ |format=mp3 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111102223612/http://www.gamepro.com/article/news/219727/roleplayers-realm-dragon-quest-25th-anniversary-edition/ |archive-date=2011-11-02 |title=Dragon Quest 25th Anniversary Edition |magazine=[[GamePro]] |date=2011-05-25 |first1=Kat |last1=Bailey |first2=Justin |last2=Haywald |first3=Ray |last3=Barnholt |first4=Tim |last4=Rogers |author-link4=Tim Rogers (journalist) |url-status=dead}}</ref>

